69_1989_songs_(P-R).html |title=SA Charts 1969 \u2013 1989 |work=rock.co.za |accessdate=1 March 2010}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n| [[Swiss Singles Chart]]<ref name=\"Au Chart\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n| [[UK Singles Chart]]<ref name=\"Au Chart\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\n|-\n| U.S. [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]<ref name=\"B Chart\">{{cite web |url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p3693|pure_url=yes}} |title=Billboard Singles |website=allmusic |accessdate=27 February 2010}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|61\n|}\n\n==Certifications==\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Italy|type=single|artist=Black Sabbath|title=Paranoid|award=Platinum|relyear=1970|certyear=2019|accessdate=2 September 2019}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United Kingdom|type=single|artist=Black Sabbath|title=Paranoid|award=Gold|relyear=1970|certyear=2019|salesamount=400,000|accessdate=2 August 2019}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom|nosales=true|noshipments=true|streaming=true}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|black-sabbath|paranoid}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Black Sabbath}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Paranoid (Song)}}\n[[Category:Black Sabbath songs]]\n[[Category:1970 singles]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Germany]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Ozzy Osbourne]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Tony Iommi]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Geezer Butler]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Bill Ward (musician)]]\n[[Category:Vertigo Records singles]]\n[[Category:1970 songs]]\n[[Category:UK Independent Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses|Paranoid (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2014}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Paranoid\n| cover      = Paranoid-The Wizard 1970 7.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Black Sabbath]]\n| album      = [[Paranoid (album)|Paranoid]]\n| B-side     = \"[[The Wizard (Black Sabbath song)|The Wizard]]\" (1970 original)\n| released   = August 1970<ref name=GRD65>{{cite book|last=Strong|first=M. C.|title=The Great Rock Discography|url=https://archive.org/details/greatrockdiscogr00stro|url-access=registration|year=1995|publisher=Canongate Books Ltd|location=Edinburgh|isbn=0-86241-385-0|page=[https://archive.org/details/greatrockdiscogr00stro/page/65 65]}}</ref>\n| format     = [[7-inch single]]\n| recorded   = 1970\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Heavy metal music|Heavy metal]]<ref>{{cite book|author=Chris Nickson|title=Ozzy Knows Best: The Amazing Story of Ozzy Osbourne, from Heavy Metal Madness to Father of the Year on MTV's \"The Osbournes\"|url=https://archive.org/details/ozzyknowsbestuna00nick|url-access=registration|date=3 August 2002|publisher=St. Martin's Press|isbn=978-1-4299-5452-5|page=[https://archive.org/details/ozzyknowsbestuna00nick/page/102 102]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ultimateclassicrock.com/best-black-sabbath-songs/|title=10 Best Black Sabbath Songs|last=Wilkening|first=Matthew|date=17 August 2011|website=Ultimate Classic Rock|access-date=11 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"RS\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/6596095/paranoid|title=Paranoid|date=December 9, 2004|website=[[Rolling Stone]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090503083902/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/6596095/paranoid|archive-date=May 3, 2009|access-date=December 23, 2018}}</ref>|[[proto-punk]]<ref name=\"RS\"/>}}\n| length     = 2:48\n| label      = [[Vertigo Records|Vertigo]]\n| writer     = {{flatlist|\n* [[Geezer Butler]]\n*[[Tony Iommi]]\n*[[Ozzy Osbourne]]\n*[[Bill Ward (musician)|Bill Ward]]\n}}\n| producer   = [[Rodger Bain]]\n| prev_title = [[The Wizard (Black Sabbath song)|The Wizard]]\n| prev_year  = 1970\n| next_title = [[After Forever (song)|After Forever]]\n| next_year  = 1971\n| misc       = \n}}\n\"'''Paranoid'''\" is a song by the British [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]] band [[Black Sabbath]], featured on their second album ''[[Paranoid (album)|Paranoid]]'' (1970). It is the first single from the album, while the B-side is the song \"[[The Wizard (Black Sabbath song)|The Wizard]]\". It reached number 4 on the [[UK Singles Chart]] and number 61 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref name=GRD65/>\n\n==About==\n\"Paranoid\" was the first Black Sabbath single release, coming six months after [[Black Sabbath (album)|their debut album]] was released. Black Sabbath bassist [[Geezer Butler]] (from ''[[Guitar World]]'' magazine, March 2004):\n\n{{quote|A lot of the ''Paranoid'' album was written around the time of our first album, ''Black Sabbath''. We recorded the whole thing in about 2 or 3 days, live in the studio. The song \"Paranoid\" was written as an afterthought. We basically needed a 3 minute filler for the album, and Tony came up with the [[riff]]. I quickly did the lyrics, and Ozzy was reading them as he was singing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lyrics007.com/Black%20Sabbath%20Lyrics/Paranoid%20Lyrics.html |title=Black Sabbath Paranoid Lyrics |publisher=Lyrics007.com |date= |accessdate=18 May 2014}}</ref>}}\n\nAccording to extant lyric sheets, \"Paranoid\" was at one time titled \"The Paranoid.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://issuu.com/riffsjournal/docs/riffs-homeofmetalzine-digitalissue/18 |title=Stolz, Nolan. 2019. \"A Rumination on Black Sabbath\u2019s Birmingham and the Value of Music Tourism.\" Riffs Journal (September): 18. }}</ref>\n\n\"Paranoid\" eventually became the name of the album, and somewhat unusually, the word ''paranoid'' is never mentioned in the lyrics. Originally the band had wanted to call the album ''War Pigs'' after the [[War Pigs|song of the same name]], but the record company persuaded them to use \"Paranoid\" instead because it was less offensive.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.last.fm/music/Black+Sabbath/_/Paranoid |title=Paranoid \u2014 Black Sabbath \u2014 |publisher=Last.fm |date= |accessdate=18 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n\"Paranoid\" was ranked No. 34 on [[VH1]]'s 40 Greatest Metal Songs.<ref>''\"VH1 40 Greatest Metal Songs\"'', 1\u20134 May 2006, ''VH1'' Channel, reported by [http://www.vh1.com/shows/dyn/the_greatest/103446/episode_this_list.jhtml VH1.com]; last accessed 10 September 2006</ref> In March 2005, [[Q magazine|''Q'' magazine]] placed it at number 11 in its list of the 100 Greatest Guitar Tracks. ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' ranked it number 250 on their list of the [[Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Songs of All Time|500 Greatest Songs of All Time]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/news/coverstory/500songs/page/3|title=The RS 500 Greatest Songs of All Time|date=9 December 2004|work=Rolling Stone|publisher=[[Jann Wenner|Wenner Media]]|accessdate=31 August 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060820114511/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/coverstory/500songs/page/3|archive-date=20 August 2006|url-status=dead}}</ref> \"Paranoid\" was ranked the fifth best Black Sabbath song by Rock - Das Gesamtwerk der gr\u00f6\u00dften Rock-Acts im Check.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Rehe |first1=Christoph |title=Rock - Das Gesamtwerk der gr\u00f6\u00dften Rock-Acts im Check: alle Alben, alle Songs. Ein eclipsed-Buch |date=2013 |publisher=Sysyphus Sysyphus Verlags GmbH |isbn=3868526463 |language=German}}</ref>\n\nThe original Black Sabbath recording has been used numerous times in various films and television shows including ''[[Sid & Nancy]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0091954/soundtrack|title=''Sid & Nancy'' soundtrack|website=IMDb.com|accessdate=28 March 2009}}</ref> ''[[Dazed and Confused (film)|Dazed and Confused]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0106677/soundtrack|title=''Dazed and Confused'' soundtrack|website=IMDb.com|accessdate=28 March 2009}}</ref> ''[[The Stoned Age]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0111293/soundtrack|title=''The Stoned Age'' soundtrack|website=IMDb.com|accessdate=28 March 2009}}</ref> ''[[Any Given Sunday]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0146838/soundtrack|title=''Any Given Sunday'' soundtrack|website=IMDb.com|accessdate=28 March 2009}}</ref> ''[[Almost Famous]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0181875/soundtrack|title=''Almost Famous'' soundtrack|website=IMDb.com|accessdate=28 March 2009}}</ref> ''[[We Are Marshall]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0758794/soundtrack|title=''We are Marshall'' soundtrack|website=IMDb.com|accessdate=28 March 2009}}</ref> ''[[The Angry Birds Movie]]'', ''[[Suicide Squad (film)|Suicide Squad]]'', ''[[Kong: Skull Island]]'' and ''[[CHiPs (film)|CHiPs]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.soundtrackmania.net/chips-soundtrack.html |title= CHiPs soundtrack {{!}} Complete List of Songs |work= Soundtrackmania.net |accessdate= June 28, 2018}}</ref> and ''[[Bad Cat]]''. The song was used in the video games ''[[Rock n' Roll Racing]]'', ''[[Guitar Hero 3]]'', ''[[Madden NFL 10]]'', ''[[WWE 2K17]]'', and ''[[Dave Mirra Freestyle BMX 2]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2001/08/16/dave-mirra-soundtrack-revealed|title=Dave Mirra Soundtrack Revealed|website=[[IGN]]|author=IGN Staff|date=2001-08-17|accessdate=2019-07-11|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190712031248/https://www.ign.com/articles/2001/08/16/dave-mirra-soundtrack-revealed|archivedate=12 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nThe song was covered by [[industrial rock]] group [[The Clay People]] for the various artists compilation album ''[[Shut Up Kitty: A Cyber-Based Covers Compilation|Shut Up Kitty]]'', released in 1993.\n\n[[Soft Cell]] was performing their cover of \"Paranoid\" on early live shows, before releasing their debut album; demo recording of the cover was released on compilation album ''[[The Bedsit Tapes]]'' in 2005.\n\nA live version by [[Doctor and the Medics]] was included on the 12\" of their single Burn, in 1986.\n\nIn [[Finland]], \"Paranoid\" has the same status as [[Lynyrd Skynyrd]]'s \"[[Free Bird]]\" in the United States as a song the audience finds humorous to request during a concert. So regardless of a band or the style of music in question, somebody may shout \"''Soittakaa 'Paranoid'!\"'' (\"Play 'Paranoid'!\") during a gig.<ref name=\"Rautio\">Timo Rautio: ''Rokatessa roiskuu osa 3'' (2004)</ref><ref>Walter De Camp: \"Sis\u00e4piiri: Walter De Campin tutkimuksia \u2013 Extreme-seksin maantiede\" An article appeared in paper ''City-lehti'', 2006, issue 20, page 26 URL: http://www.city.fi/artikkeli/Sis%E4piiri/2124/{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Personnel==\n* [[Ozzy Osbourne]] \u2013 vocals\n* [[Tony Iommi]] \u2013 rhythm and lead guitars\n* [[Geezer Butler]] \u2013 bass\n* [[Bill Ward (musician)|Bill Ward]] \u2013 drums\n\n==Accolades==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Publication\n! Country\n! Accolade\n! Year\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Rank\n|-\n| [[NME]]\n| United Kingdom\n| \"All Time Top 100 Singles\"<ref name=nme>{{cite web|url=http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/nme_readers.htm |title=NME Lists |work=rocklistmusic.co.uk |accessdate=13 March 2010}}</ref>\n| 1976\n| 41\n|-\n| [[Spin magazine|Spin]]\n| United States\n| \"100 Greatest Singles of All Time\"<ref name=spin>{{cite web|url=http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/spin100.html#singles89 |title=Spin: 100 Greatest Singles Of All Time (1989) |work=rocklistmusic.co.uk |accessdate=13 March 2010}}</ref>\n| 1989\n| 81\n|-\n| [[Radio Veronica]]\n| [[Netherlands]]\n| \"Super All-Time List\"<ref name=rv>{{cite web|url=http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/veronica.html |title=Super All-Time List \u2013 From 1989 |work=rocklistmusic.co.uk |accessdate=13 March 2010}}</ref>\n| 1989\n| 16\n|-\n| [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame|Rock and Roll<br> Hall of Fame]]<br>\n| United States\n| \"The Rock and Roll Hall of Fame's 500 Songs<br> that Shaped Rock and Roll\"<ref name=rnr>{{cite web|url=http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/steveparker/halloffame.htm |title=500 Songs That Shaped Rock |work=rocklistmusic.co.uk |accessdate=13 March 2010}}</ref><br>\n| 1994\n| *\n|-\n| [[Guitarist (magazine)|Guitarist]]\n| United Kingdom\n| \"Top 100 Guitar Solos of All-Time\"<ref name=gl>{{cite web|url=http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/50.html |title=Guitar Lists |work=rocklistmusic.co.uk |accessdate=13 March 2010}}</ref>\n| 1998\n| 84\n|-\n| [[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]\n| United States\n| \"500 Greatest Songs of All Time\"<ref name=rs>{{cite web|url=http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/rstone.html#500Songs |title=The Rolling Stone 500 Greatest Songs of All Time |work=rocklistmusic.co.uk |accessdate=13 March 2010}}</ref>\n| 2004\n| 250\n|-\n| [[Q (magazine)|Q]]\n| United Kingdom\n| \"1010 Songs You Must Own!\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/q1010songs.htm |title=1010 Songs You Must Own! |accessdate=14 March 2010 |work=rocklists.net}}</ref>\n| 2004\n| *\n|-\n| [[Q magazine|Q]]\n| United Kingdom\n| \"100 Greatest Guitar Tracks Ever!\"<ref name=q>{{cite web|url=http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/qlistspage3.htm |title=Q Lists |work=rocklistmusic.co.uk |accessdate=19 September 2015}}</ref>\n| 2005\n| 11\n|-\n| [[Q magazine|Q]]\n| United Kingdom\n| \"100 Greatest Songs of All Time\"<ref name=ql>{{cite web|url=http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/qlistspage3.htm |title=Q Lists |work=rocklistmusic.co.uk |accessdate=13 March 2010}}</ref>\n| 2006\n| 100\n|-\n| [[VH1]]\n| United States\n| \"40 Greatest Metal Songs\"<ref name=vh1ms>{{cite web|url=http://www.listology.com/list/40-greatest-metal-songs-vh1-made-decent-effort |title=40 Greatest Metal Songs (VH1 made a decent effort) |work=listology.com |accessdate=13 March 2010}}</ref>\n| 2006\n| 1\n|-\n| [[VH1]]\n| United States\n| \"100 Greatest Hard Rock Songs\"<ref name=vh1>{{cite web|url=http://stereogum.com/43591/vh1s_100_greatest_hard_rock_songs/list/ |title=VH1's 100 Greatest Hard Rock Songs |work=stereogum.com |accessdate=13 March 2010}}</ref>\n| 2008\n| 4\n|}\n\n<small>(*) designates unordered lists.</small>\n\n==Track listing==\n*'''7\" single <small>(Vertigo 6059 010)</small>'''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sabbath.se/Discography/paranoidvinyl7.html |title=Paranoid Vinyl 7\" Discography |work=sabbath.se |accessdate=13 March 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090813165418/http://sabbath.se/Discography/paranoidvinyl7.html |archivedate=13 August 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n# \"Paranoid\" \u2013 2:45\n# \"The Wizard\" \u2013 4:20\n\n*'''7\" single <small>(Vertigo 6059 014)</small>'''\n#\"Paranoid\" \u2013 2:50\n#\"Rat Salad\" \u2013 2:30\n\n*'''7\" singles <small>(Vertigo AS 109)</small>'''\n#\"Paranoid\" \u2013 2:50\n#\"Happy Being Me\"{{ref label|Happy Being Me|I|}} \u2013 15:54\n\n*'''7\" 1977 re-release <small>(Immediate 103 466)</small>'''\n#\"Paranoid\" \u2013 2:50\n#\"[[Evil Woman (Crow song)|Evil Woman]]\" \u2013 3:25\n\n*'''7\" 1977 re-release <small>(Nems SRS 510.044)</small>'''\n#\"Paranoid\" \u2013 2:50\n#\"Tomorrow's Dream\" \u2013 3:11\n\n*'''7\" 1980 re-release <small>(Spiegelei INT 110.604)</small>'''\n# \"Paranoid\" \u2013 2:45\n# \"Snowblind\" \u2013 5:25\n\n'''Note'''\n*'''I'''{{Note|Happy Being Me}} \"Happy Being Me\" is performed by [[Manfred Mann Chapter Three]] and appears on their second album [[Manfred Mann Chapter Three Volume Two]].\n\n==Charts==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1970)\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Peak<br>position\n|-\n| Australian [[Go-Set|Go-Set National Top 60]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.poparchives.com.au/gosetcharts/1971/19710227.html |title=27&nbsp;February 1971 Singles |work=poparchives.com.au |accessdate=1 March 2010}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|18\n|-\n| [[Austrian Singles Chart]]<ref name=\"Au Chart\">{{cite web |url=http://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Black+Sabbath&titel=Paranoid&cat=s |title=Black Sabbath \u2013 P